======================================================================
PHASE 5: BACKUP & MAINTENANCE
======================================================================

Step 5.1: Create Backup Script
------------------------------
Create a batch file named BackupMySQL.bat on the server:

@echo off
REM MySQL Backup Script for Store Parts
setlocal

set MYSQL_PATH="C:\Program Files\MySQL\MySQL Server 8.0\bin"
set DB_USER=root
set DB_PASS=YourRootPassword
set DB_NAME=MainDB
set BACKUP_FOLDER=C:\DatabaseBackups\StoreParts
set DAYS_TO_KEEP=30

REM Create backup folder if not exists
if not exist "%BACKUP_FOLDER%" mkdir "%BACKUP_FOLDER%"

REM Generate timestamp
set TIMESTAMP=%date:~-4%%date:~4,2%%date:~7,2%_%time:~0,2%%time:~3,2%%time:~6,2%
set TIMESTAMP=%TIMESTAMP: =0%

REM Backup filename
set BACKUP_FILE=%BACKUP_FOLDER%\%DB_NAME%_%TIMESTAMP%.sql

echo ========================================
echo MySQL Backup - Store Parts Database
echo ========================================
echo Date: %date% %time%
echo Backing up to: %BACKUP_FILE%
echo.

REM Run mysqldump
%MYSQL_PATH%\mysqldump.exe -u %DB_USER% -p%DB_PASS% %DB_NAME% > "%BACKUP_FILE%"

if %ERRORLEVEL% EQU 0 (
    echo Backup completed successfully!
    echo File: %BACKUP_FILE%
) else (
    echo ERROR: Backup failed!
)

REM Clean old backups
echo.
echo Cleaning backups older than %DAYS_TO_KEEP% days...
forfiles /p "%BACKUP_FOLDER%" /s /m *.sql /d -%DAYS_TO_KEEP% /c "cmd /c del @path && echo Deleted: @file" 2>nul

echo.
echo Done!
echo %date% %time% - Backup: %BACKUP_FILE% >> "%BACKUP_FOLDER%\backup_log.txt"

endlocal
pause

---

Step 5.2: Schedule Automatic Backups
------------------------------------
1. Open Task Scheduler (taskschd.msc)

2. Click "Create Task"

3. General tab:
   - Name: MySQL Store Parts Backup
   - Run whether user is logged on or not
   - Run with highest privileges

4. Triggers tab:
   - New → Daily at 11:00 PM → OK

5. Actions tab:
   - New → Start a program
   - Program: C:\DatabaseBackups\BackupMySQL.bat
   - OK

6. Click OK, enter password

7. Right-click task → Run (to test)

---

Step 5.3: Restore from Backup
-----------------------------
If you need to restore:

1. Open Command Prompt as Administrator

2. Navigate to MySQL bin folder:
   cd "C:\Program Files\MySQL\MySQL Server 8.0\bin"

3. Run restore command:
   mysql -u root -p MainDB < "C:\DatabaseBackups\StoreParts\MainDB_20240115.sql"

4. Enter root password when prompted

5. Database will be restored

---

Step 5.4: Database Maintenance
------------------------------
Run monthly in MySQL Workbench:

-- Optimize tables for better performance
OPTIMIZE TABLE MainDB.machinery_item_inward_unit2;
OPTIMIZE TABLE MainDB.PartsUsageHistory;
OPTIMIZE TABLE MainDB.PartyMaster;
OPTIMIZE TABLE MainDB.ItemMaster;
OPTIMIZE TABLE MainDB.MachineMaster;
OPTIMIZE TABLE MainDB.PersonMaster;

-- Check for errors
CHECK TABLE MainDB.machinery_item_inward_unit2;
CHECK TABLE MainDB.PartsUsageHistory;

-- Sync used_qty from history (if needed)
UPDATE MainDB.machinery_item_inward_unit2 p
SET used_qty = IFNULL((
    SELECT SUM(quantity_used) 
    FROM MainDB.PartsUsageHistory 
    WHERE inward_item_id = p.id
), 0);

SELECT 'Maintenance complete!' AS Result;

---

======================================================================
PHASE 6: TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE
======================================================================

Issue 6.1: Cannot Connect from Client PC
----------------------------------------
Symptoms:
- "Unable to connect to host"
- "Connection refused"
- Timeout errors

Solutions:

A. Verify server is running:
   - On server, check services.msc
   - MySQL80 service should be "Running"

B. Test network connectivity:
   - On client, open Command Prompt
   - Run: ping 192.168.1.100 (use server IP)
   - Should see replies, not "Request timed out"

C. Test MySQL port:
   - On client, run: telnet 192.168.1.100 3306
   - If connects (weird characters appear): Port is open
   - If "Could not open connection": Firewall blocking

D. Check firewall on server:
   - Ensure port 3306 is allowed inbound
   - See Step 1.10

E. Verify user can connect remotely:
   - In MySQL Workbench on server, run:
     SELECT User, Host FROM mysql.user WHERE User = 'storeparts';
   - Host should be '%' (any host)
   - If not, run: CREATE USER 'storeparts'@'%' IDENTIFIED BY 'StoreParts@123';

---

Issue 6.2: "Access denied for user"
-----------------------------------
Symptoms:
- "Access denied for user 'storeparts'@'192.168.1.x'"

Solutions:

A. Verify password is correct:
   - Password is case-sensitive!
   - Default: StoreParts@123

B. Grant privileges again:
   - On server, in MySQL Workbench:
     GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON MainDB.* TO 'storeparts'@'%';
     FLUSH PRIVILEGES;

C. Reset user password:
   ALTER USER 'storeparts'@'%' IDENTIFIED BY 'NewPassword123';
   FLUSH PRIVILEGES;

---

Issue 6.3: MySQL Service Won't Start
------------------------------------
Unlike SQL Server Express, MySQL rarely has this issue, but if it happens:

A. Check error log:
   - Go to: C:\ProgramData\MySQL\MySQL Server 8.0\Data
   - Open the .err file with Notepad
   - Look for errors at the end

B. Check if port is in use:
   - Command Prompt: netstat -ano | findstr 3306
   - If another process is using it, stop that process

C. Run MySQL as Administrator:
   - Stop MySQL service
   - Open Command Prompt as Admin
   - cd "C:\Program Files\MySQL\MySQL Server 8.0\bin"
   - mysqld --console
   - Watch for errors

D. Reinstall (last resort):
   - Uninstall MySQL from Control Panel
   - Delete C:\ProgramData\MySQL folder
   - Delete C:\Program Files\MySQL folder
   - Reinstall following Phase 1

---

Issue 6.4: Application Shows "Database not found"
-------------------------------------------------
Solutions:

A. Verify database exists:
   - Open MySQL Workbench
   - Connect to server
   - Check if "MainDB" appears in SCHEMAS

B. Run database setup script again:
   - Copy script from Step 1.6
   - Execute in MySQL Workbench

C. Check connection string in app:
   - Database name is case-sensitive in some configs
   - Should be: MainDB

---

Issue 6.5: Slow Performance
---------------------------
Solutions:

A. Run optimization (Step 5.4)

B. Check network:
   - Use wired connection, not WiFi
   - Ensure gigabit network if possible

C. Increase MySQL memory (on server):
   - Edit my.ini file
   - Increase innodb_buffer_pool_size
   - Restart MySQL service

---

======================================================================
PHASE 7: ADVANCED CONFIGURATION
======================================================================

Step 7.1: Change MySQL Port (if needed)
---------------------------------------
If port 3306 is blocked or in use:

1. Open MySQL Workbench

2. Connect to server

3. Run: SHOW VARIABLES LIKE 'port';
   (Shows current port)

4. To change port:
   - Edit my.ini file (C:\ProgramData\MySQL\MySQL Server 8.0\my.ini)
   - Find [mysqld] section
   - Change: port=3306 to port=3307
   - Save file
   - Restart MySQL service

5. Update firewall rule for new port

6. Update all client connection strings

---

Step 7.2: Configure Static IP on Server
---------------------------------------
Important for production! Prevents IP changes.

1. Press Windows + R, type: ncpa.cpl, Enter

2. Right-click your network adapter → Properties

3. Select "Internet Protocol Version 4" → Properties

4. Select "Use the following IP address"

5. Enter:
   - IP address: 192.168.1.100 (your server IP)
   - Subnet mask: 255.255.255.0
   - Default gateway: 192.168.1.1 (your router)
   - Preferred DNS: 8.8.8.8
   - Alternate DNS: 8.8.4.4

6. Click OK → OK

---

Step 7.3: SSL Encryption (Optional)
-----------------------------------
For secure connections over network:

1. MySQL 8.0 has SSL enabled by default

2. To verify, in MySQL Workbench run:
   SHOW VARIABLES LIKE '%ssl%';

3. To force SSL connections:
   ALTER USER 'storeparts'@'%' REQUIRE SSL;
   FLUSH PRIVILEGES;

---

======================================================================
PHASE 8: USER MANAGEMENT
======================================================================

Step 8.1: Default Login
-----------------------
- Username: admin
- Password: admin

Step 8.2: Creating Database Users
---------------------------------
To create additional MySQL users:

-- Create user for specific PC (more secure)
CREATE USER 'user1'@'192.168.1.101' IDENTIFIED BY 'Password123';
GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE ON MainDB.* TO 'user1'@'192.168.1.101';

-- Create user for any PC
CREATE USER 'user2'@'%' IDENTIFIED BY 'Password456';
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON MainDB.* TO 'user2'@'%';

FLUSH PRIVILEGES;

